What happened is completely normal after using:

```python id="zcnuy8"
pd.get_dummies()
```

You converted categorical columns into machine-learning-friendly numerical columns.

This is actually GOOD practice for ML.

But there are a few things you should improve.

---

# What Happened?

This line:

```python id="nnhn6g"
df = pd.get_dummies(df, columns=['department','gender','city'], drop_first=True)
```

transformed text categories into binary columns.

Example:

Before:

| department |
| ---------- |
| HR         |
| IT         |
| Sales      |

After:

| department_Hr | department_It | department_Sales |
| ------------- | ------------- | ---------------- |
| True          | False         | False            |
| False         | True          | False            |

This is called:

# One-Hot Encoding

Used heavily in machine learning.

---

# Why It Looks Ugly

Because now:

* too many columns
* booleans everywhere
* hard to read
* not human-friendly anymore

This is NORMAL.

ML models like numbers, not pretty tables.

---

# The REAL Problem

You accidentally encoded high-cardinality features too aggressively.

Example:

```text id="s87r8g"
city_Boston
city_Chennai
city_Chicago
city_Delhi
...
```

Now the dataset becomes wide.

On huge datasets this becomes inefficient.

---

# What Professionals Usually Do

## Small categories → One-hot encoding

Good:

```text id="t2zhff"
gender
department
```

because few unique values.

---

## Large categories → avoid full one-hot encoding

Cities may have:

* 100
* 1000
* 10000 unique values

Then one-hot encoding becomes bad.

Instead professionals use:

* Label Encoding
* Target Encoding
* Embeddings
* Frequency Encoding

depending on ML model.

---

# Another Important Thing

Your columns became:

```text id="i3qqvj"
department_Hr
department_It
```

because earlier you used:

```python id="b3yzix"
.str.title()
```

So:

```text id="woc9g0"
HR → Hr
IT → It
```

That is why encoded columns look weird.

Better:

```python id="5e03fm"
df['department'] = df['department'].str.upper()
```

Then columns become:

```text id="xqspm4"
department_HR
department_IT
```

much cleaner.

---

# Another Hidden Issue

Your dummy columns are boolean:

```text id="z1i8jp"
True / False
```

Many ML workflows prefer integers.

Use:

```python id="u8x3za"
df = pd.get_dummies(
    df,
    columns=['department','gender','city'],
    drop_first=True,
    dtype=int
)
```

Then:

```text id="jlwmgi"
1 / 0
```

instead of:

```text id="1tbtyt"
True / False
```

